@Dingfelder Smurfalot I agree. My Dad had a massive stroke in 1995 at the age of 48 while working as a truck driver. Just a few months shy of my parents 30th Wedding Anniversary. He couldn't afford his blood pressure medication & his family Dr. could've provided him with free samples but didn't. Us kids were unaware of our parents financial situation because Dad was too proud to ask for help. I was on College summer break at the time & was expecting a visit from them in one week. Following his stroke, he spent 6 months in a hospital then another 6 months in a rehab facility to learn how to do basics again. Such as talking. He was left paralyzed on one side & suffered short term memory loss. He was instantly retired and they were plunged into poverty. They eventually moved into a low income handicap housing unit. Mom took very good care of him. I looked out for her. In 2011, he was diagnosed with rectal cancer. He had been showing signs but again was too embarrassed to tell Mom he was bleeding from his bum. He underwent radiation & chemotherapy but the cancer was in stage 3 by this time. My Uncle came to visit before Dad's surgery. He was my Mom's brother. He started asking Mom about the signs etc. He returned home to see his own Dr. He had stage 4 rectal cancer. Dad's surgery was in July. My Uncle passed away in November only 4 months later. Dad continued to recover in hospital but was eventually moved to a long-term care facility. It was there, two weeks later a nurse had trouble waking him up one morning. They rushed him back & it was discovered his system had become septic. They couldn't do anything for him. Sent him back to the long-term care facility & put him on end of life care. We were told we had maybe a week left with him. We had him for 6 more weeks before he passed on Easter Sunday in 2012. My point is that many Men are embarrassed to admit they can't afford medication or are embarrassed to discuss certain physical problems they are experiencing. The stigma needs to end. Men need to be able to open up & have real conversations about concerning issues without feeling awkward about it. A man should be able to approach their peers & confide that they have a problem with domestic violence at home or a concerning medical issue without fear of being laughed at or emasculated. I raised my two sons on the "Brothers Forever" philosophy. They are 21 & 20. Teaching them that friends & girls will come & go throughout their lives, but a brother will be there forever. They in turn have extended this bond to include some of the guys they grew up with. Essentially if one of them has a problem,  they all know about it & help each other to find a solution or offer support. It's a Bro code they follow. They have even gone as far as to extend that help to other young men who find themselves lost & unable to cope. One young man almost gave up. He overdosed & drank a bottle of rye. Posted some crazy goodbye stuff on social media. He was not part of their circle but they had gone to school together. My boys & their buddies raised the alarm & started a search party. They found him in the field behind the High School. Rushed him to the local hospital & contacted the boys Mom. They stuck with her until the news that he would be ok was told by the attending Dr. He is now part of the circle. They are always checking in with him like they check in with each other. I believe that they set the example of how a Man should bond with other Men. How to stick together & support each other. They also keep each other in line. I see these friendships lasting a lifetime. It's time for Men everywhere to step up & talk to each other. I mean really talk to each other. I've known too many that showed outwardly they were ok & the next thing you knew, they had committed suicide. Tomorrow I am going to call my siblings & do my own checks. Then I'll start on my list of friends. A phone call can make all the difference.
Love it!  But these days you can't even get equal cancer research for men, or meet to discuss men's issues without someone pulling a fire alarm.
